  • Karen
    5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Still love it after 2 years of ownership
    Reviewed in the United States on July 8, 2018
    Updated: I've had this for 2 years and still love it. It's indispensable for keeping my farm animals safe, seeing what's going on around the property day and night. Our setup is 16 cameras with total 2500 feet of cable; The cameras have been out in the rain,... See more
    Updated: I've had this for 2 years and still love it. It's indispensable for keeping my farm animals safe, seeing what's going on around the property day and night. Our setup is 16 cameras with total 2500 feet of cable; The cameras have been out in the rain, snow, ice, summer heat, dust and still work great.

    Reolink support has been awesome - only needed them a couple of times over the past 2 years -- first was a mysterious config issue which they diagnosed and solved; the second was last week when the transformer went out. We're out of warranty now but they still helped to diagnose the issue and we're back in action.

    Just having it out of commission for a few days showed us how much we rely on it. Being able to see that all is well inside the barns at 2am - wonderful. Even have a camera on the homing pigeons (yeah) - so fascinating to see them doing their thing when humans aren't around.

    We still just sit and watch it. If we have visitors, we all sit and watch it. Ok, that may be weird.

    Here's my original review --

    Day 3 and I love it. I started intending to buy 1 camera, bought 8, added 4 more. Now up to 12 and figuring out that I need (ok, want) more. My use is for farm cam to keep an eye on animals, so night vision/audio/POE and being affordable enough for multiple locations were my key purchase requirements. Has already brought invaluable peace of mind, and is just plain fun to watch (yes, we sit watching the security cameras). The color image is very nice; the night vision is great. I have it inside a goat barn, horse barn and pigeon loft and it is very clear even in nighttime low light (when it goes to black & white). I don't know that it would be mug shot level quality, but I do know I can tell which goat is being bad in the dark goat barn now. Also have it on several outdoor areas, where it's color late into the evening.

    Instructions are simple, but too simple and lacking some detail I would have liked; would have been nice to note somewhere that password needs a number (and special character?). Without any error message, that was just trial and error. Kind of a bummer for first experience with it, but once I was through that bit, everything else was so easy. POE is the way to go. Can't believe I even pondered on that for a day or two like I did. Installing a camera is literally 3 screws, drilling a hole for cable if needed, plugging in the cable on the camera to the ethernet cable, then the ethernet cable to the DVR - done! The DVR defaulted to auto add, so wait a few seconds and the new camera shows up. Maybe I'll put it on the internet sometime (and I can see from other reviewers that can be a project), but for now, straight out of the box and not connected to my network does exactly what I want.

    Some other notes --
    1. Another reviewer noted that the trick to audio is to make sure the DVR is set to record audio in addition to the camera being turned on for audio - very helpful.
    2. I dropped one camera (yes I did) and it wasn't damaged at all. These seem sturdy.
    3. After figuring out the 3-way articulation, it was easy to set up cameras pointing exactly where I wanted them. Though I went through a phase where things were at various angles (kind of modern art) then realized the barrel rotates too so now everything's level.
    4. The packaging was hilarious. Did they have a competition to see how much equipment would fit into the smallest box? Everything was well packed and nothing was even out of place. It was just the densest packing job I've seen for a while.
    5. Really glad I got the 16-channels because now I realize that everything needs to have a camera on it.... meadow, woods, pond....how did we get by without this?
    6. The night vision gives such a peace of mind; that was one reason I bought this particular camera system. These cameras have 36 IR LEDs, so more than the usual.

    An added bonus (other than not having to go out to the barn at 2am to check on them) is being able to see the amount of animal stuff that happens when humans aren't around.... fascinating
    65 people found this helpful

  • Mr. fixit
    5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Great home system - REALLY Easy Setup!!!
    Reviewed in the United States on July 13, 2017
    Received promptly with two extra dome cameras, as ordered. This is my third system - same location, just keep upgrading to new, better technology. My initial reaction is that this is a great system for home surveillance. I haven't disconnected and replaced the... See more
    Received promptly with two extra dome cameras, as ordered. This is my third system - same location, just keep upgrading to new, better technology. My initial reaction is that this is a great system for home surveillance. I haven't disconnected and replaced the existing one yet but it should be easy as I was already using Ethernet cables (but I had to put converter baluns at each end - now I can just remove those and use existing cat5 and cat 6 cables). But I have fired it up on my desk and connected it to internet and all 10 cameras to be sure all was working.

    I have to say, while I'm pretty techie and have set up two prior systems, I was AMAZED at how simple and fast it was to set this up for access on my home network PC's, and on my iPhone and iPad. I used a DDNS internet setup in the past but did not need it for this system. It basically just set itself up once I downloaded the PC program and the iOS apps. I refuse to buy anything that has to use the manufacturer's website for internet access - with or without a fee. This works purely over internet with no need to go through REOLINK's servers - perfect! Some other popular brands are not so flexible.

    Cameras appear way more clear and sharp than my existing system. I ordered 2 extra cameras - the RLC-422 dome cameras with zoom. I have zoom cameras now but you have to use a small screwdriver at the camera to change the zoom to suit the location. I was surprised to find that these can be zoomed remotely using the software. Very nice - and focus adjusts automatically when zoom is changed.

    Came with virtually everything I needed - you'll want to get a small monitor to connect to the NVR (I got a lightweight 21.5" HDMI full HD monitor for about $100 that sits nicely on top of the NVR) as my existing one was ancient technology.

    I did upgrade the NVR firmware to one released less than a month ago - very easy to do but be aware that it will take around 45 minutes with no indication of progress. I was about to e-mail their support when it beeped that it was done and then re-started. Had to re-enter all of the set-up info. so do this before you get too far into things.

    So far, I'm very happy with this purchase, especially for the price - a good value compared to other more advertised brands.

    I bought and installed this system just about exactly one year ago, in September 2019. I installed the system myself. I bought two extra cameras so I have 10 cameras installed all together. Running the wiring through the house was the biggest part of the labor because it is... See more
    I bought and installed this system just about exactly one year ago, in September 2019. I installed the system myself. I bought two extra cameras so I have 10 cameras installed all together. Running the wiring through the house was the biggest part of the labor because it is installed in a two-story house with 10 cameras mounted outside to cover the entire outside of the house. The system was fairly easy to set up and to get up and running. I had a few questions which Reolink technical support answered quickly.

    The technical information and instructions that came with the system a year ago were not super detailed but they were adequate. They pretty much told you what you needed to do, but if you had questions about it, there wasnt much depth to the instructions to explain any questions that you might have. Like I said any questions I had, I just emailed to Reolink, and I typically got an answer back within a day. I found the technical support to be extremely responsive and very capable.

    There are lots of other reviews about how well the system works so I wont go into all that here. Please see my review for the Reolink POE Camera 5MP Super HD 4X zoom camera under the user name of WD that discusses my experience with trying to use the cameras for motion detection alarms being pushed to my iPhone or email. If youre planning to do that, please read that review. In a nutshell, cameras using this technology really dont work well for motion detection when the cameras are mounted outside. The cameras detect changes in the pixels in the camera image and interpret those changes as motion. That means that bugs, wasps, moths, spiderwebs, sun movement, cloud movement, and everything else that moves in the picture can cause a motion alarm. You can try to filter that by setting up detection zones and adjusting the sensitivity, but the technology just doesnt work well for motion detection outside. When the sun changes the shadows on your front porch, or a shadow from a cloud passes over your front yard, a whole bunch of the pixels change, and theres nothing you can do to filter that out. After playing with it for months and trying all kinds of different settings, I finally turned the alarm notifications off so the only motion alarms I get go to the NVR so I can look at them later if I want to. Having the alerts go to your cell phone or your email just blows up your cell phone and email incoming messages. This is NOT a reflection on Reolink, its just the way this technology works. I did quite a bit of research on the Internet about trying to solve this problem, and apparently thats just the way it is. There dont seem to be any good answers out there.

    All in all though, the system works fantastic.

    After my system had been installed for about nine months, I had video loss on all the cameras at the same time. Working through the problem with Reolink we figured out that the NVR was bad, and after one or two email exchanges they arranged for Amazon to send me a brand new NVR. No hassle, no headache, easy as pie. Amazon even shipped the new NVR to me immediately, before I had sent back the old one. I am not sure, but the problem with the NVR may have been caused by a thunderstorm that we had in the vicinity around the time of the NVR went bad.

    At any rate, I am very happy with the system and very happy with a Reolinks technical support. They really seem to go out of their way to be responsive and to help you out.

    One more comment about motion detection. What I finally settled on was using infrared motion detectors outside that sounded a voice alarm inside the house, to alert me when somebody is on the front porch or on the breezeway. These work well because they use infrared technology and only alarm when they detect a sudden temperature change in front of the sensor. So now if somebody walks up on my front porch, the Reolink system is of course recording the video of that happening, the infrared motion detector sounds an alert inside the house, and I can get on my iPhone, iPad, or NVR System monitor, and look and see whos out there. This set up has worked really well for me. Of course if youre not home you dont know that somebody walked up on the front porch at the time of the event. But if you notice anything strange, you can go to the NVR system and look at all the alerts that happened during that time frame and it will have captured that motion detection alarm and video on the NVR. The infrared motion detection system that I am using is a Voice Alert System 6 that I bought through Amazon. It handles up to six channels and allows you to record voice alerts to tell you which channel is going off.

    At any rate, I am happy with this Reolink system. Given its relatively low cost and the capabilities that it has, I am well satisfied. If I ever get around to it I might add another camera or two, and install a second HDD so it will store more data. With 10 cameras feeding the NVR it records about four or five days of video, which is all that I really need right now.

    Reviewed in the United States on June 11, 2018

    I sincerely regret purchasing this product. I bought it in August of 2016 and had it professionally installed in September. Within 3 months the hard drive failed and I had my first communication with Reolink support. They sent me a completely new NVR and instructed me to either swap the hard drive or swap the unit. I swapped the hard drive and asked then on 3 separate occasions what to do with the defective NVR. Never received a response and it is still sitting in my garage.

    In February of 2017 the wired mouse that comes with the NVR went out. Being that it is USB I tried a few wireless mice from Logitech but couldnt get any of them to work. Reolink support recommended 2 specific models from Logitech which I purchased, neither one worked. I ended up using the mouse from the replacement NVR even though the outer casing of it was fractured. Super glue as least partially resolved that.

    In March of 2018 I purchased 4 more cameras, bringing the total to 12 and again, professionally installed. Within 3 weeks one of the brand new cameras went out, just stopped recording and would not turn on. Reolink support asked me to send them the defective camera and they would ship out a new one. I informed then that I already spent $150 per camera to install it and was not keen on doing this a second time to pull it off and a third to reinstall. After 6-10 email exchanges where I was repeatedly asked to send in the defective one first by whomever was working that day I finally informed them that I was ready to pursue resolution with Amazon. Thats when I met Justine from Reolink support who finally took the time to read through the exchanges and understand what the issue was; you sold me a defective camera and I need a new one before you get the old one. She had a replacement camera shipped out to me straight away, whereupon I called the installer back out to swap them.

    After the swap I asked Reolink where to send the defective camera to and they provided an address in the Los Angeles area. When I asked how I was to ship it I was told You may need contact USPS or FedEx to collect the package after you are ready for it, they will let you know the return shipping fee and which account you need to pay. Please kindly noted that your order has passed 30 days from delivery date for free shipping, the customer need cover the return shipping fee. After another 6-10 emails I was told that I could keep the defective camera if it was too much trouble to send it back but to please kindly provide a review on Amazon for their products.

    Well then, here is my actual review in order of significance:

    - Support is absolutely terrible. There is a bit of a language barrier but the issue is that they do not even pay attention to what you are saying and dont look toward resolution. Level 2 or 3 support is better but still a problem.
    - Crap shoot as to whether you will get a functioning NVR or not
    - Crap shoot as to whether you will get a functioning camera or not
    - The cameras go through periodic reboots where they stop recording entirely
    - The picture on the NVR of the cameras will occasionally go dark, even though the cameras are still recording (Thankfully!)
    - The NVR UI is very clunky and somewhat difficult to navigate through
    - NVR is not compatible with any wireless mouse that I tested
    - Mouse provided with NVR is cheap and falls apart
    - Phone app is easier to use than the NVR for general views in real time but is cumbersome when you are trying to review playback of recorded video
    - Phone app must be attached to Wi-Fi in order to view any video. If not, good luck using a phone to view recorded video.
    - Has a 3TB hard drive but with 12 cameras (on a 16 channel NVR no less) the video was only retained for about 30 hours. Adding an additional 4TB internally gave me 6 additional days of recorded video
    - No cloud storage yet

    This is a great system! My setup: The 8 cameras that came with the system, and one PTZ camera. I have had the system setup for about 3 months now. The cameras have a very high resolution, and are extremely clear. The setup is also very easy and there is no need to worry about any dynamic dns to access it from the internet with the UID feature. That was a huge plus. The iphone application is very easy to use and also very useful. The interface is also very easy to use and the PC application is pretty good. The setup, interface, and quality of this system is far superior to other systems I have setup and used in the past.

    Now for the things I don't like, and the reason why it didn't get 5 stars. The cameras are a little "laggy" even on the internal network. One of the eight cameras was defective and would not switch to night mode or day mode automatically, but they replaced the camera for me free of charge, except for I had to pay shipping for the returned camera. The PC application could use some refinements. I tried to use a wireless mouse on the system itself, but it didn't work. I think that this would be a big future improvement.

    All in all though, I would buy this system again.

    Thinking of video security?? This is the one!
    Reviewed in the United States on December 30, 2017

    If you have need of a security camera system this is the one. I spent hours researching and checking out different systems in person. Overall this system stood out significantly over others. Pros: - higher resolution. This is so extremely important.... See more
    If you have need of a security camera system this is the one. I spent hours researching and checking out different systems in person. Overall this system stood out significantly over others.

    Pros:
    - higher resolution. This is so extremely important. Higher the resolution means that you can see identifying information from further distances. Most systems stop at HD 1080 or 720. Reolink takes is another step past that.
    - PoE. Power over Ethernet allows extremely fast install as you only have one cable to run for the signal back to the recorder AND power. It also means that any holes you need to cut in your walls are much smaller.
    - The quality of the Ethernet cable is very nice, very flexible and easy to pass through tight spaces.
    - Multiple ways to access the video feed. Bring able to use my laptop/desktop, phone, tablet, or the Reolink recorder to access the interface and recordings is really nice. Especially when it came time to position the cameras. Bring able to see the camera view in my phone made the process a cinch.
    - The motion tracking system is great for maximising the recording time and minimising unneeded recordings and alerts.
    - Plenty of other cameras for specific needs that are 100% compatible and just plug.
    - Lots of extra ports for more cameras

    Cons: ( these are rather minimal)
    - mounting screws strip very easily. This is a very common problem with screws in general now days. I really suggest not bothering with the included ones and great a pack of number 6 wood screws
    - Setting the motion sensitivity is a little tricky. Not really a complaint, but it does take a fair amount of tinkering to get it right for your needs. I suggest taking your time and don't expect to get it correct the first time.
